rt List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maxWidthRamp(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Create a list of tuples (value, index) and sort it by value\n        indexed_nums = sorted((num, idx) for idx, num in enumerate(nums))\n        \n        # Initialize the maximum width and the minimum index\n        max_width = 0\n        min_index = float('inf')\n        \n        # Iterate through the sorted list to find the maximum width ramp\n        for num, idx in indexed_nums:\n            max_width = max(max_width, idx - min_index)\n            min_index = min(min_index, idx)\n        \n        return max_width\n```\n\nThis solution works by first creating a list of tuples where each tuple contains a number and its index from the input list `nums`. This list is then sorted based on the numbers. As we iterate through this sorted list, we keep track of the minimum index encountered so far and calculate the potential ramp width at each step. The maximum width is updated accordingly. This approach ensures that we efficiently find the maximum width ramp with a time complexity of O(n log n) due to the sorting step.", "estimated_date": 1545523200000}